data.body:
I was debugging an issue in my application and found that I was creating too many Pixmaps for my phone to handle. It was however difficult to get this information, because the app simply closes, there is no error message and nothing in LogCat. The same happens on the Desktop, if you push it to its limit.

The following code reproduces the issue (just put it in any app's initialization code):

``` java
ArrayList<Pixmap> list = new ArrayList<Pixmap>();

while(true) {
    list.add(new Pixmap(file));
    System.out.println("List size:    " + list.size());
}
```

Please improve error handling for this condition, so that an app can at least display a meaningful error message. Preferably an exception should be thrown on the Java side.

The screen doesn't render any graphics after you risize using Gdx.graphics.setDisplayMode().
This only happens if you are drawing nothing into the screen, only using glClear to show a background color.

Using the source example for a new libgdx project

``` java
public class MyGdxGame extends ApplicationAdapter {
    SpriteBatch batch;
    Texture img;

    @Override
    public void create () {
        batch = new SpriteBatch();
        img = new Texture("badlogic.jpg");

        Gdx.graphics.setDisplayMode(800, 600, false); //<- Change display mode
    }

    @Override
    public void render () {
        Gdx.gl.glClearColor(1, 0, 0, 1);
        Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);
        batch.begin();
//      batch.draw(img, 0, 0); //<- do not render anything besides the glClear
        batch.end();
    }
}
```

Using the above code will show an empty window with no rendering. If you uncomment the batch.draw() line, the background will render again.

notes: I'm on Linux 32 using the latest stable release.

After recent changes Json parser parse an empty array [] as an array with one empty string inside. So the code:

<pre><code>static class Container
{
    Array<String> items;
}

...

String json = "{ \"items\":[] }";
new JsonReader().parse(json);</code></pre>


Results in: { items: [""] }, while the expected result is: { items: [] }.
